            <div id="myHeader" style="background-color: #fed780;padding: 20px;margin: 10px;">
              <p style="color: #3D5161;font-family: Tahoma;">Reach shines the spotlight on the incredible women of Irish sport. First off, our marketing team celebrated local heroines throughout the country who are making significant strides for women's sports in Ireland. RSVP invited readers to nominate the unsung champions of women's sports ‚Äì those who toil behind the scenes. From the nominations, a shortlist of 10 finalists were identified and put to a public vote with over 2000 votes cast. The victor emerged as the chairman of Donegal Town FC, an organisation boasting 400 members, committed to enhancing the mental well-being of people within that club

 <br> <img src=https://github.com/jamesleahyreachplc/TheLoop/blob/main/Aug/World%20Cup%20Sky%20.jpg?raw=true style="width:51%;margin-top:10px;margin-bottom:10px;"><br>

<br><br>While on the subject of women's sports, the editorial team wanted to give a big shout-out to Sandra Mallon who is pictured with her trophy for Most Improved Player of the season at Sword Women's Rugby club. Not to be confused as it was by some envious rivals for another showbiz reporting gong. And though it was back in May we can't not mention Zoe Watson who picked up the Women's Championship Manager of the year award at the Northern Ireland Futsal Federation awards. 
<br><br>t wasn't all play and no work as summer has seen another string of big stories and great editorial energy. We've had journalists joining peacekeeping forces in Lebanon and reporting from the scene of the tragic deaths of hundreds of migrants in Greece. At home the Irish Daily Star/Irish Mirror campaign to highlight rising violence against women has been recognised by the Taoiseach and Justice Minister, and is a good example of a great collaborative effort across the newsroom. We've also led the way on a summer of big stories from the sad deaths of Christy Dignam and Sinead O'Connor to the crisis in RTE. Not to mention Danny De Vall who courageously donned helmet and flak jacket to report from the the frontline of the battle of Drogheda , a town besieged by seagulls. It even earned him an honourable mention as reporter of the day on the morning paper reviews. Where Seagulls Dare! 


<br><br>We plan to add a few more social gatherings at the office for chats and catch-ups in the coming weeks so hope to see more faces in Talbot Street which - contrary to rumours that even the seagulls go around in pairs - is actually not that bad!
